    <div id="homecontent">
        <div style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">
            <h2> I would love to accept your invitation and join you, but I ask that you read this first and consider if you can accommodate my chemical injury.</h2>
            <br /><br />
            
			Ever see the movie <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0258470/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1" target="_blank">Bubble Boy</a>? The beginning of that movie is a 
            lot like what my life has become due to my chemical injury. While I don&#39;t need a hamster ball to survive, my body can no longer deal with the 
            <a  href="http://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms?cdrid=687391" target="_blank">toxicants</a> found in everyday life.
            <br /><br />
            
			This condition is called <a href="http://www.ei-resource.org/illness-information/environmental-illnesses/multiple-chemical-sensitivity/" 
            target="_blank">MCS/EI</a> or <a href="http://drclaudiamiller.com/about-tilt/" target="_blank">TILT</a> and it impacts where I can go, who I can 
            be around, and how I must take care of myself.
            <br /><br />
            
			It&#39;s not that I don&#39;t enjoy the company of others, but the chemicals that are in most American products make me ill. The chemicals used 
            in clothes and personal products make me feel like I have the flu, and the more people there are around me, the worse it gets. 
            <a href="http://peggymunson.com/mcs/myths.html" target="_blank">Here&#39;s a helpful link</a> if you want to know more.)
            <br /><br />
            
			Chemicals in clothes and personal products? Yes. It&#39;s amazing.
            <br /><br />
            
			Laundry detergent and fabric softeners often have scents (chemicals) that are designed to make the clothes smell fresh for a long time. 
            Then there&#39;s cologne, perfume, scented soaps, lotions, not to mention air fresheners and candles. The list goes on and on, and I can give 
            you more information if you want it. All of them have a negative impact on my quality of life.
            <br /><br />
            
			Being around any of these chemicals, in even small amounts, will give me a headache. Literally.
            <br /><br />
            
			And that&#39;s only the start. Fogginess of mind, forgetfulness, fatigue. The presence of these chemicals can even make my joints ache.
            <br /><br />
            
			Higher concentrations are much worse. Nausea, burning eyes, tunnel vision, irregular heart rhythm. Sometimes, I can&#39;t even talk because I am unable to form words.
            <br /><br />
            
			It all depends on the concentration of the chemicals present and how long I&#39;m exposed to them.
            <br /><br />
            
			I also have to be very careful around petroleum products. Gas, oil, and exhaust from engines. New building materials like paint, flooring, 
            plastics, and wood products made with binders. It&#39;s amazing how many petrochemicals are a part of our lives.
            <br /><br />
            
			I would like to spend time with you, but I need to make sure that I can do so without hurting.
            <br /><br /><br />
            
            
